{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f66a49d6-6c97-4545-9827-ed837862f5d3","content":"Here's the approach for tracing .NET 8 in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` in the container\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process and collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps                       # find the PID\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n### 4. Copy the trace file out\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace.nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### 5. Analyze\nOpen the `.nettrace` file in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert it:\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n### Tips\n- If the container image lacks the .NET SDK, use `dotnet tool install` with `--tool-path` and ensure the runtime matches.\n- For **event-based** collection (GC, exceptions, contention), use `--profile gc-verbose` or `--providers` to specify EventSource providers.\n- If `dotnet-trace` can't connect (e.g., diagnostic port issues), set `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` or fall back to **`dotnet-counters`** first to verify connectivity.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0b919b6d-5144-4315-a54b-264af4eac1f7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":426,"requestId":"63C7:353DA2:14612CA:17AF2B6:69EC1455"},"id":"443dfe58-8e33-4285-a75f-f11e5cd9eebd","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:09:52.922Z","parentId":"2b1769c0-cd69-4415-bbc3-62e1f96340b0"}
